Below is a clean and professional step-by-step guide for implementing Argo CD in a Kubernetes environment.

I have also replaced the real passwords and tokens with placeholders. Avoid storing actual passwords or tokens directly in documents or scripts. Since credentials were shared in the command text, it is recommended to rotate them before using this in production.

 Argo CD Implementation Guide

 1. Purpose

This document explains the step-by-step process to install and configure Argo CD in a Kubernetes cluster.

Argo CD will be used to deploy applications using the GitOps approach. The Kubernetes manifests will be stored in a Git repository, and Argo CD will continuously monitor the repository and sync changes to the Kubernetes cluster.

 2. Prerequisites

Before starting the implementation, ensure the following are available:

* Kubernetes cluster access
* `kubectl` configured on the master or bastion server
* Helm installed
* GitLab manifest repository access
* Harbor registry credentials
* Argo CD CLI access
* Required namespaces created in Kubernetes
* GitLab runner configured, if GitLab CI/CD is used

 3. Add the Argo Helm Repository

Add the official Argo Helm repository:


helm repo add argo https://argoproj.github.io/argo-helm


Update the Helm repository:


helm repo update


 4. Create the Argo CD Namespace

Create a dedicated namespace for Argo CD:


kubectl create namespace argocd


 5. Install Argo CD Using Helm

Install Argo CD using Helm:


helm upgrade --install argocd argo/argo-cd -n argocd


Verify that the Argo CD pods are running:


kubectl get pods -n argocd


Check the Argo CD services:


kubectl get svc -n argocd


 6. Get the Initial Argo CD Admin Password

Run the following command to get the initial admin password:


argocd admin initial-password -n argocd


Save the password securely. It will be required to log in to Argo CD.

 7. Install the Argo CD CLI

Download the latest Argo CD CLI binary:


curl -sSL -o /usr/local/bin/argocd \
  https://github.com/argoproj/argo-cd/releases/latest/download/argocd-linux-amd64


Give execute permission:


chmod +x /usr/local/bin/argocd


Verify the Argo CD CLI installation:


argocd version --client


 8. Access the Argo CD Server

If the Argo CD service is not exposed externally, use port forwarding:


kubectl port-forward svc/argocd-server -n argocd 8080:443


Keep this terminal session running.

Now log in to Argo CD from another terminal:


argocd login localhost:8080 \
  --username admin \
  --password '<ARGOCD_ADMIN_PASSWORD>' \
  --insecure


Replace:

text
<ARGOCD_ADMIN_PASSWORD>


with the password received from the initial password command.

 9. Verify GitLab Runner Status

If GitLab CI/CD is part of the deployment flow, verify that the GitLab runner services are running:


systemctl status gitlab-runsvdir



systemctl status gitlab-runner


If the runner is not running, start and enable it:


systemctl start gitlab-runner
systemctl enable gitlab-runner


 10. Prepare the Manifest Repository Structure

The Kubernetes manifest repository should be organized clearly.

Example structure:

text
DevOps-Manifest/
└── kubernetes-manifest/
    └── ordermutationmsapi/
        └── dev/
            ├── namespace.yaml
            ├── deployment.yaml
            ├── service.yaml
            └── kustomization.yaml


In this example:

* `ordermutationmsapi` is the application name
* `dev` is the target environment
* `deployment.yaml` contains the Kubernetes Deployment
* `service.yaml` contains the Kubernetes Service
* `namespace.yaml` contains the namespace definition
* `kustomization.yaml` manages the manifest resources and image updates

 11. Create a GitLab Project Access Token

Go to the Kubernetes-manifest GitLab project.

Navigate to:

text
Settings > Access Tokens > Add new token


Create a new token with the following details:

text
Token name: gitlab-ci-manifest-writer
Role: Maintainer
Scope: write_repository


After creating the token, copy it immediately. GitLab shows the token value only once.

 12. Add GitLab CI/CD Variables

Add the following variables in the GitLab project where the CI/CD pipeline is running:

text
MANIFEST_REPO_USER
MANIFEST_REPO_TOKEN


Example:

text
MANIFEST_REPO_USER  = <GITLAB_USERNAME_OR_TOKEN_USER>
MANIFEST_REPO_TOKEN = <GITLAB_PROJECT_ACCESS_TOKEN>


These variables will be used by the pipeline to update the image tag in the manifest repository.

 13. Create Harbor Image Pull Secret

Create the target application namespace if it does not already exist:


kubectl create namespace dev


Create the Harbor registry secret in the `dev` namespace:


kubectl create secret docker-registry harbor-regcred \
  --docker-server=<HARBOR_REGISTRY_URL> \
  --docker-username=<HARBOR_USERNAME> \
  --docker-password='<HARBOR_PASSWORD>' \
  -n dev


Example:


kubectl create secret docker-registry harbor-regcred \
  --docker-server=10.48.209.136 \
  --docker-username=admin \
  --docker-password='<HARBOR_PASSWORD>' \
  -n dev


Verify the secret:


kubectl get secret harbor-regcred -n dev


 14. Add the Manifest Repository to Argo CD

Add the GitLab manifest repository to Argo CD:


argocd repo add http://10.48.209.150/LR-POC/DevOps-Manifest/kubernetes-manifest.git \
  --username <GIT_USERNAME> \
  --password '<GIT_PASSWORD_OR_TOKEN>' \
  --insecure-skip-server-verification


Verify that the repository has been added successfully:


argocd repo list


 15. Create the Argo CD Application Manifest

Create a file named:


argocd-application.yaml


Add the following content:

yaml
apiVersion: argoproj.io/v1alpha1
kind: Application
metadata:
  name: ordermutationmsapi-dev
  namespace: argocd
spec:
  project: default

  source:
    repoURL: http://10.48.209.150/LR-POC/DevOps-Manifest/kubernetes-manifest.git
    targetRevision: main
    path: ordermutationmsapi/dev

  destination:
    server: https://kubernetes.default.svc
    namespace: dev

  syncPolicy:
    automated:
      prune: true
      selfHeal: true
    syncOptions:
      - CreateNamespace=true


Explanation:

text
name: Argo CD application name
namespace: Argo CD namespace
repoURL: Git repository where Kubernetes manifests are stored
targetRevision: Git branch to track
path: Manifest folder path inside the repository
destination.namespace: Kubernetes namespace where the app will be deployed
prune: Removes resources from the cluster if they are removed from Git
selfHeal: Automatically fixes manual changes made directly in the cluster
CreateNamespace=true: Creates the namespace automatically if it does not exist


 16. Apply the Argo CD Application

Apply the Argo CD application manifest:


kubectl apply -f argocd-application.yaml


Verify that the application was created:


kubectl get application.argoproj.io ordermutationmsapi-dev -n argocd


You can also check the application using the Argo CD CLI:


argocd app get ordermutationmsapi-dev


 17. Enable Automated Sync

Automated sync is already enabled in the YAML file. However, you can also enable it using the CLI:


argocd app set ordermutationmsapi-dev --sync-policy automated


Enable self-healing:


argocd app set ordermutationmsapi-dev --sync-policy automated --self-heal


Enable pruning:


argocd app set ordermutationmsapi-dev --auto-prune


 18. Sync the Application

Run the first manual sync:


argocd app sync ordermutationmsapi-dev


Check the application status:


argocd app get ordermutationmsapi-dev


The application should show:

text
Sync Status: Synced
Health Status: Healthy


 19. Verify the Application in Kubernetes

Check resources in the `dev` namespace:


kubectl get all -n dev


Check pods:


kubectl get pods -n dev


Check services:


kubectl get svc -n dev


Check deployment:


kubectl get deployment -n dev


 20. Validate GitOps Flow

To confirm that Argo CD is working correctly:

1. Update the image tag or manifest file in the Git repository.
2. Commit and push the change to the `main` branch.
3. Argo CD will detect the change.
4. The application will automatically sync to the Kubernetes cluster.
5. Verify the rollout:


kubectl rollout status deployment/<DEPLOYMENT_NAME> -n dev


Example:


kubectl rollout status deployment/ordermutationmsapi -n dev


 21. Useful Argo CD Commands

Check Argo CD applications:


argocd app list


Get application details:


argocd app get ordermutationmsapi-dev


Sync application manually:


argocd app sync ordermutationmsapi-dev


Check repository list:


argocd repo list


Delete an application from Argo CD:


argocd app delete ordermutationmsapi-dev


Check Argo CD pods:


kubectl get pods -n argocd


Check Argo CD services:


kubectl get svc -n argocd


 23. Final Implementation Flow

The complete flow will work as follows:

text
Developer pushes code
        ↓
GitLab CI/CD builds the image
        ↓
Image is pushed to Harbor
        ↓
Pipeline updates image tag in manifest repository
        ↓
Argo CD detects manifest repository change
        ↓
Argo CD syncs the application to Kubernetes
        ↓
Application is deployed in the target namespace


This completes the Argo CD implementation process.
